entry.title: Fix gpu_unittests running under UBSan
entry.content:
This is mostly a mess of alignment/type-punning issues. First, random

pointers cannot be cast to uint32_t* because they won't be aligned.

Instead, type-punning loads and stores can be done through memcpy.



Second, packed structs are very irritating when combined with EXPECT_EQ.

It isn't safe to take a pointer to a field in a packed struct, but

EXPECT_EQ internally does so. Copy fields to temporary values before

passing to EXPECT_EQ.

entry.title: [Hub] Add shrink and expand animation support
entry.content:
Create shrink and expand animations for Hub. These are borrowed from

TabSwitcherLayout, but the implementation is much more ergonomic.



The ShrinkExpandHubLayoutAnimatorProvider owns and attaches a

ShrinkExpandImageView to the HubContainerView. This view is initially

invisible.



If a bitmap is needed a bitmap callback is created that will set the

image on the ShrinkExpandImageView when ready. This callback uses weak

references to prevent retaining refs to the view or the animator

provider in the event it gets held in native for a prolonged duration

and the fallback animator runs.



The animator provider waits for the bitmap and some asynchronously

supplied data regarding initial and final rects for the animation to

be supplied. The external caller can also cancel the animation to use

the fallback through this supplier. This is a holdover from the

TabSwitcherLayout which must skip an animation is the

TabListRecyclerView has too much work to do and can hopefully be

removed in the future.



Once the animator provider has all the data it will supply the

Animator. Unless a fallback animation is requested beforehand in which

case a fade animation will be provided for the shrink/expand case or

the animation will proceed in the case of the new tab animation.

entry.title: [X11] Move utils into x11::Connection
entry.content:
The motivation for this CL is to eventually move ui/base/x/x11_util

into x11::Connection. x11_util has a lot of utilities that perform

frequent blocking calls (eg WmSupportsHint() is called on every mouse

event in the non-client area). A simple x11::PropertyCache is

sufficient to avoid blocking, but ownership of the cache becomes

an issue since x11_util only contains free functions. In the GPU

process, x11_util may be used from multiple threads with their own

connections, so we really need a per-connection cache. The current

solution avoids the issue because x11::Connection::Get() gets the

TLS Connection instance to do each blocking call.

entry.title: Leave inflow position alone when resuming a parallel flow.
entry.content:
ComputeInflowPosition() would reset the margin strut, and thus we'd lose

the MarginStrut::discard_margins flag. This flag is set to truncate

margins at unforced breaks, and needs to remain true as long as we

haven't added any in-flow content to the next fragmentainer. The bug was

that the block-start margin of some child would be re-applied after an

unforced break, because this flag was reset prematurely.



The crash in crbug.com/1494668 was caused by this correctness issue. It

caused inline elements to become non-contiguous unexpectedly. E.g.

there's a fragment item for a SPAN in the first and the third columns,

but not in the second, due to a large margin, that should have been

ignored.

entry.title: Fenced frames: Relax the enrollment requirement for post-impression
entry.content:
reporting beacons.



Post-impression beacons problem:

Currently reporting beacons sent from reportEvent API and automatic

beacons are required to have their destinations enrolled. The destination sites are considered enrolled if and only if they are

attested for the Protected Audience API. This means even if the recipient is not using any ads personalization or targeting features

of Protected Audience, the attestation is still required.



This CL changed the attestation requirement to either Protected

Audience or Attribution Reporting. The AdTech who needs to receive

such beacons is allowed to be attested for Attribution Reporting in order to satisfy the enrollment requirements.



Note: This should NOT apply to beacons from reportWin() and

reportResult().



This change is gated on a default-off feature.



Some drive-by fixes:

1. In test ReportEventCustomURLDestinationNotEnrolled, the beacon is

not sent because there the custom reporting origin is disallowed, not

because of failing the enrollment check, which is what this test is supposed to test. This is because when join the interest group, there

is only "a.test" in the allowedReportingOrigins, but not the

reporting destination "d.test".



2. PrivacySandboxSettingsEventReportingBrowserTest does not validate

the console errors. This CL implemented the checks on console errors.

To do this, a fenced frame reporter observer is added. This is needed

because we need to observe whether a reporting beacon is queued to be

sent later. If queued, the console error message will not be emitted.



See discussion on this issue here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Z5shfSVVZv5mrCAa4-ORAkbbTxMTpXbBpC136Rjobqw/edit#heading=h.aqe8meqngjxv

entry.title: Fix mojo_unittests running under UBSan
entry.content:
memcpy(NULL, NULL, 0) is UB due to a C language bug we're, for now,

stuck with. std::copy doesn't have this problem, but since this code

is dealing with a lot of void* pointers, I've just added a check for

empty length.



Type-punning via pointer casts is both a strict aliasing violation (not

relevant for Chromium) but also casting unaligned pointer cannot be

created.



To that end, the alignment situations in OptionsValidationTest.Invalid

are actually UB to even set up. For now, I've just suppressed UBSan in

those tests, but it would be legal for a compiler to delete the

alignment checks on ground that every T* value is required to be aligned

by virtue of existing.

The global Core object is only initialized when ipcz is off. The

other Core tests did this, but we missed GetTimeTicksNow because it

happened to work by way of an unused null this pointer in the method.

entry.title: Fix content_unittests errors under UBSan
entry.content:
This, along with

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4987645, seems

to make content_unittests pass under UBSan. Issues fixed:



- memcpy(NULL, 0) and memcmp(NULL, 0) is undefined due to a C language

bug. Use C++ functions instead, which avoid this bug. Where easy, I've

used ranges and span functions, which are a bit more bounds-aware.



- Casting a random character buffer to char16_t* for type-punning is not

safe. It's undefined both by strict aliasing (though Chromium disables

that), and also because it is invalid to create a T* pointer that is

insufficiently aligned for T. Instead, do the conversions after

loading the values. While I'm here, replace some resize +

pointer-based calls to reserve + push_back, which is safer. (E.g. we

don't need to consider whether the length calculation overflows.)



- EXPECT_EQ on a packed struct has alignment issues because the

macro internally takes a reference to the values. That reference

is unaligned in a packed struct. (Packed structs are very difficult

to use correctly.)

entry.title: Revert "Improve backdrop filter calculations in SkiaRenderer"
entry.content:
This reverts commit bbbcef0fd5821181da6374a6c3d28394c21083a0.



Reason for revert: possibly breaking https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1497384



Original change's description:

> Improve backdrop filter calculations in SkiaRenderer

>

> Pulls all of the bounds analysis for how to clip the output and input

> of a backdrop filter into the CalculateRPDQParams function. Improves

> the calculations for the `filter_bounds` value to be tighter for

> backdrop filters since their output is always restricted.

>

> Optimizes more cases to have backdrop output restricted by just a

> clip instead of introducing an image filter node at the end. Switches

> the input cropping node from a no-op Offset(0,0) to a proper `Crop`

> that can define the boundary tilemode to apply (kClamp). This

> actually fixes the behavior in the backdrop-offset unit test. It also

> makes it possible to easily experiment with using mirror tiling for

> content that is off screen.

>

> Re-organizes some of the logic for clipping or clearing the backdrop

> bounds into helper functions in RPDQParams so that

> PrepareCanvasForRPDQ is more readable.

>

> The backdrop logic to determine if an input crop is needed or not

> used to have a bug (exposed when removing the staging flag

> SK_USE_LEGACY_CONTENT_BOUNDS_PROPAGATION). The input bounds

> calculation needs to use a null src rect so that the returned value

> has no additional content restriction. If it *still* matches the

> target output bounds, then we know it's not a pixel-moving backdrop

> filter. I confirmed that the backdrop boundary layout tests work

> correctly with and without the above staging flag.

>

> Updates the conversion of FilterOperations to PaintFilter to define

> the tiling geometry, so that clamp, mirror, and repeat explicitly

> apply to the edges of a layer (instead of previously just the edge

> of whatever image size happened to come through the pipeline). This

> currently is only taken advantage of in SkiaRenderer,

> SoftwareRenderer continues to use the legacy (less stable/defined)

> tiling behavior.

entry.title: Fuzzing coverage: increase RSS limit.
entry.content:
When run on ClusterFuzz, fuzzers obey extra parameters inside an

.options file which can specify things like a per-fuzzer customized RSS

limit. We don't have that parsing and configuration code available to us

in the LUCI environment, so for now, hard-code a larger RSS limit for

all fuzzers.



This is necessary because we see some fuzzers (e.g.

html_preload_scanner) crashing in the logs by using excessive RSS. It's

not clear whether this is because they naturally use more than the 2GB

default or if it's because specific test cases cause extreme memory

usage (and whether that's a bug). However, such crashes appear to result

in coverage information not being fully written out, thus resulting in

inaccuracies in the fuzzing coverage dashboard.



While we investigate how and whether we can persuade such fuzzers to

write out coverage information even in case of a crash, meanwhile tweak

the RSS limit to perhaps reduce such crashes in the first place.
